WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.000
But in Utah, we have a great place to practice, we have great scenery, but we also have GVHD.

00:00:08.000 --> 00:00:11.000
We have not ridden that yet, so it's not perfect.

00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:20.000
But I wanted to just go over a project that was initiated by an observation of some of our nurse practitioners

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:26.000
and our faculty that looked at latitude GVHD and its onset in patients.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:36.000
As background, Dr. Marta Arora at the University of Minnesota has already described this in the past as early as 2016 and even before,

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:42.000
where they looked at incidents in a fairly large amount of patients, 511 people,

00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:49.000
and saw that the varieties of GVHD that are out there, it's just not the normal stuff that we all anticipate,

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:56.000
that we all were trained with, but there's also a later variety that seems to kind of either herald the onset

00:00:56.000 --> 00:01:01.000
of GVHD or the overlap syndrome that we've all become aware of.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:11.000
And it's something that either persists and is harder to treat, and so it leads to more complications in most large series.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:20.000
And so in 2024, as we were ending the year, we looked back and saw an increased incidence of that latitude GVHD.

00:01:20.000 --> 00:01:25.000
And so this group wanted, our group wanted to take a look at, was there something that we were doing different?

00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:30.000
Was there something that changed? And how can we overcome this issue?

00:01:30.000 --> 00:01:33.000
Because it had not been a problem in other years.

00:01:33.000 --> 00:01:41.000
And so a retrospective analysis was designed that looked at the patient journey, 281 patients in total,

00:01:41.000 --> 00:01:49.000
and with a planned sub-analysis that's yet to be finished of 62 transplants done in 2024,

00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.000
looking at how did the T-cell kinetics change, or how did the T-cell population change?

00:01:54.000 --> 00:02:00.000
Just on regular routine chimerism analyses that we tend to do,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:08.000
of either CD33 fractions and the CD3 fraction, or an unsorted group with CD3.

00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:17.000
And so a rather busy slide to highlight kind of the left lower order onset of GVHD,

00:02:17.000 --> 00:02:23.000
defined as "late," meaning no overlap from chronic GVHD whatsoever,

00:02:23.000 --> 00:02:25.000
and anything that was after day 100.

00:02:25.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Typically, those patients are falling in Utah up until that point.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:34.000
And then, as you heard from a colleague of mine, Dr. Barron, in a previous discussion,

00:02:34.000 --> 00:02:41.000
we have this five shade area that patients are longing to get back to their home that we transplant in.

00:02:41.000 --> 00:02:46.000
And so once they go back, the attack tapers that are established by us and by the PharmDs,

00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:52.000
whether that's absolutely followed, hit or miss followed, what happens to those patients when they go back?

00:02:52.000 --> 00:02:59.000
And so we were able to come up with fairly detailed characteristics of these patients,

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:05.000
but shown very wide ranges of T-cell kinetics, or T-cell measurements, if you will,

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:11.000
between day 100 and day 180, and the shifts that happen thereon.

00:03:11.000 --> 00:03:21.000
This led to the identification of about 10, now going up into 12, on further analysis of the data,

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:26.000
and seeing that there was quite severe acute GVHD.

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:34.000
And it was noticeable in the 29 patients that we found that the change in that T-cell kinetics

00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:44.000
from day 100 to day 180 seemed to predict a higher incidence of not only mortality, 64% compared to 33%,

00:03:44.000 --> 00:03:50.000
but also the organ, which was affected, honestly.

00:03:50.000 --> 00:03:52.000
And so, we did a lot of research on that.

00:03:52.000 --> 00:03:55.000
We did a lot of research on the T-cell kinetics in those patients,

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:59.000
